When I said I’d ordered a peppermint hot cocoa, the woman (named Quinn, I believe) loudly announced that I “said peppermint mocha.” When I said I hadn’t said that, she once again loudly announced that I’d ordered a peppermint mocha but she “guessed they could remake it.” She was incredibly rude. Is the customer always right? Honestly, no. But in this instance I was. Learn to handle situations better, Quinn. Especially when you’re the one who messed up. I won’t be giving this Starbucks my business again.

I had been coming here sporadically for several years, ever since I moved into the neighborhood in 2004, but it's only been more recently--once I lost my job in finance--that I began to make a habit of frequenting this café regularly, albeit mostly for the WiFi.  I'm Brazilian-born, so Starbucks coffee has never impressed me--they're basically overpriced--and, to me, concoctions adding whipped cream to coffee are anathema. Japanese kissaten are vastly superior. (I taught ESL in Kyushu for 14 months.) I actually used to think its founder had been influenced by them, what with Seattle being along the Pacific Rim, but then I discovered the chain's Italian inspiration.  I make it a habit of picking up trash all over the neighborhood, including off this blessed Starbucks' sidewalk. (I can't stand litter; again, Japanese influence.) When here, I often hold the door open for nannies or parents with strollers, pick trash up off their floor, wipe down their service counter--putting their sugar and spice dispensers in their proper place--as well as milk carafes back in order of thickness/cream content (half & half; whole milk; non-fat). Any empties immediately go on the specialized coffee pick-up counter for their attention/refilling.  I personally composte all my fruit and vegetable waste regularly, and have  volunteered to take their coffee grounds to the collection bins at the green market which assembles at nearby Cadman Plaza on Saturdays. This billion dollar corporation, however, cannot be bothered setting an example for the rest of the country, so it's all sent directly to landfills, along with those ubiquitous plastic lids. (Incidentally, has anyone checked whether they're really BPA-free?) Starbucks doesn't recycle either; their indoor bins are merely a front/whitewashing. Notice their clear plastic bags on the sidewalk at night: Everything is just mixed together.  The absolute last straw, however, was their blatant pettiness. The doors to the cabinets below the service counter have loose fixtures without any cushioning behind them to dampen the noise as they're being closed. Nearly every barista here habitually slams every one of these doors as he/she wipes down the counter and replenishes the containers with sugar, Splenda, etc. We customers jump as each door bangs shut. It's inconsiderate and obnoxious.  I had begged several of them to add felt pads to the doors; a dozen typically cost less than $5.00 at any hardware store. I have such things on all my own cabinets, as well as acrylic ones under all my furniture legs. Hell, this huge corporation could easily afford to install actual dampers. After several requests had fallen on deaf ears, I simply took it upon myself to buy pads and cushion each door. It was done in early evening, while all staff were obviously immersed in their own banter. They often create quite a ruckus while chatting and clanging cookware towards the back of the coffee shop. A male customer actually watched and laughed, then gave me a thumbs up as I took my leave.  Long story short, EVERY PAD has now been removed and baristas are back to assaulting our eardrums. Manager Ashley even took it upon herself to inform me that I shouldn't touch anything... This country is just too litigious for its own good.  I don't usually make it a habit of writing vituperative screeds on the internet; in fact--this is a first--but this latest incident was too galling. I guess I will no longer be spending time at this establishment.  Alternatives: Le Pain Quotidien (a Belgian chain, which uses real dishes) on Montague Street, although it has only 1 outlet w/ a surge protector at their communal table; Maison Kayser (French) at 57 Court Street; Paris Baguette (a case of Koreans copying the Japanese, who--in turn--copied the French) at 97 Court Street, corner Schermerhorn; 2 Tazza(s), at 72 Clark Street or 311 Henry (nearly at corner with Atlantic Avenue), albeit NO WiFi at either; or Vineapple at 71 Pineapple Street, nearly at the corner with Henry Street.
